1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:27,102
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

2
00:00:32,667 --> 00:00:35,832
I'm using this book by Bhikkhu Bodhi and the Buddha's Words.

3
00:00:36,231 --> 00:00:37,173
It's a nice collection.

4
00:00:38,454 --> 00:00:44,444
And his translations are very clear and he's got good notes on it.

5
00:00:47,848 --> 00:00:50,412
The chapter I'm looking at is Approaching the Dharma.

6
00:00:52,215 --> 00:00:53,838
About stuff that I'm sure you've heard about.

7
00:00:53,997 --> 00:00:55,219
No dogma, no belief.

8
00:00:55,240 --> 00:00:57,944
But I thought we'd just have a look at the scriptures on it.

9
00:00:58,585 --> 00:00:59,585
But before we start,

10
00:01:02,182 --> 00:01:08,528
little categorization here which may be of small interest.

11
00:01:09,149 --> 00:01:15,835
There are, if you take five types of ideologies for want of a better word.

12
00:01:17,337 --> 00:01:25,126
So a fundamentalist, we all know what a fundamentalist is, basically they think theirs is the only true mountain.

13
00:01:26,828 --> 00:01:30,552
So you think you're actually climbing a mountain but really you're descending into a pit.

14
00:01:31,087 --> 00:01:31,929
That's their point of view.

15
00:01:34,474 --> 00:01:37,117
Um, it's a case of I'm right, everybody else is wrong.

16
00:01:38,200 --> 00:01:40,382
So, obviously, there's going to be contradiction and conflict.

17
00:01:42,266 --> 00:01:47,495
Then you get this relative fundamentalist who has respect for the traditions.

18
00:01:47,674 --> 00:01:49,218
Yeah.

19
00:01:49,237 --> 00:01:52,903
Uh, and they're all mountains, but my mountain is bigger and better.

20
00:01:54,606 --> 00:01:54,686
See?

21
00:01:54,706 --> 00:01:55,408
Whereas, um,

22
00:01:55,927 --> 00:01:58,831
Whereas yours will stop short, mine will actually reach the ultimate goal.

23
00:01:58,852 --> 00:02:01,635
At some point, you've got to come across and join my mountain.

24
00:02:03,858 --> 00:02:08,044
That even happened to me in India, you know, with a Tibetan monk.

25
00:02:09,146 --> 00:02:15,816
He told me that the Theravada path is all right, but, you know, if I wanted really to make it, I'd have to become a Mahayana.

26
00:02:20,163 --> 00:02:21,884
Then there's a relativist.

27
00:02:23,164 --> 00:02:28,451
So really the relativist is in a sense acknowledging their ignorance of other religions.

28
00:02:29,834 --> 00:02:33,900
And they usually say all mountains are equal but they're all different.

29
00:02:33,960 --> 00:02:34,599
And it's up to you.

30
00:02:34,741 --> 00:02:36,242
It's all relative.

31
00:02:38,085 --> 00:02:40,087
And there's no way of telling which is more true to the other.

32
00:02:40,108 --> 00:02:52,024
I mean the only way realistically a person can decide whether your path is better or less good as their path is by actually doing it.

33
00:02:53,016 --> 00:02:57,066
actually reaching the end by some teacher in a path saying, yes, this is the end.

34
00:02:57,586 --> 00:02:59,751
And they said, well, hold on, I went one step further.

35
00:03:00,092 --> 00:03:01,495
And this is what happened to the Buddha, remember?

36
00:03:02,056 --> 00:03:05,402
He went along to these teachers and they all said, yeah, you've got it.

37
00:03:06,385 --> 00:03:08,509
We want you to teach, we want you to be part of our faculty.

38
00:03:09,793 --> 00:03:13,640
And he felt they hadn't quite made it and he left them.

39
00:03:13,957 --> 00:03:15,118
That was two teachers, wasn't it?

40
00:03:16,259 --> 00:03:19,002
And then there was the mortification stuff, you see.

41
00:03:19,021 --> 00:03:20,943
That was also another path at the time.

42
00:03:21,644 --> 00:03:27,789
Probably best exemplified by the Niganta, the person who founded the Jains.

43
00:03:28,871 --> 00:03:34,194
And even that he found wanting, he just said it was more suffering.

44
00:03:34,215 --> 00:03:37,016
Then there's the relativist universalist.

45
00:03:39,399 --> 00:03:43,763
And the person says, well, if you look below the surface of culture and words,

46
00:03:44,349 --> 00:03:47,074
And you find that actually all religions are on the same mountain.

47
00:03:48,515 --> 00:03:50,699
Because eventually they're all saying the same thing.

48
00:03:52,442 --> 00:03:57,430
Although each path is distinct and separate going up the mountain, you're always actually on the same mountain.

49
00:03:59,032 --> 00:04:03,459
So you find that especially between this conjunction between Christianity and Buddhism.

50
00:04:03,498 --> 00:04:08,907
There's a lot of work done by a lot of people trying to connect them.

51
00:04:10,405 --> 00:04:13,167
trying to find a way, and there's books on it of course.

52
00:04:13,287 --> 00:04:15,810
I mean even Thich Nhat Hanh threw his lot in, didn't he?

53
00:04:16,089 --> 00:04:16,790
What was it called?

54
00:04:17,050 --> 00:04:18,891
Buddha.

55
00:04:19,172 --> 00:04:24,055
But anyway, there's lots of these efforts, both at a very high theological level.

56
00:04:25,658 --> 00:04:27,238
When I say high, I mean academic.

57
00:04:28,300 --> 00:04:35,206
And at an actual practice level where a lot of Christians practice meditation.

58
00:04:35,466 --> 00:04:38,168
A lot of Christians practice vipassana.

59
00:04:39,670 --> 00:04:40,209
But

60
00:04:41,016 --> 00:04:43,319
I don't see it going the other way.

61
00:04:43,600 --> 00:04:44,822
I don't see much going the other way.

62
00:04:44,841 --> 00:04:57,759
In fact, I read an article about this, where the person was saying there was so much connection between Christianity and Buddhism, and that a lot of Christians were...

63
00:04:57,778 --> 00:05:10,095
I mean, I'm not putting a percentage on it, just a lot of Christians practiced Buddhist things, but he hadn't seen Buddhists move over to...

64
00:05:10,209 --> 00:05:12,072
Things like belief in God and all that.

65
00:05:12,091 --> 00:05:13,793
And a practice of praying to God.

66
00:05:13,814 --> 00:05:15,716
If you don't believe in God, there's no point in praying to him.

67
00:05:18,579 --> 00:05:18,899
Anyway.

68
00:05:19,641 --> 00:05:23,165
And then finally, there's the universalist.

69
00:05:24,004 --> 00:05:27,369
Not the relative universalist, like yours is equal.

70
00:05:27,689 --> 00:05:30,273
There's actually, I would say, the universalist.

71
00:05:31,874 --> 00:05:37,821
Who sees clearly that beneath all these rites and rituals, customs, cultures and all that, there are in fact just three ways.

72
00:05:38,358 --> 00:05:44,305
And that's the way of insight, the way of knowledge, the way of love, and the way of action.

73
00:05:44,867 --> 00:05:45,668
Usually they're all together.

74
00:05:46,048 --> 00:05:50,014
And if you look at the eightfold path, they're there.

75
00:05:50,293 --> 00:05:51,937
You start off with right understanding.

76
00:05:53,939 --> 00:06:02,430
You have right attitude, which is always described as selfishness to generosity, hatred to love, cruelty to compassion.

77
00:06:02,610 --> 00:06:05,415
Those are the three examples that come with it.

78
00:06:05,435 --> 00:06:06,677
And then you have, of course...

79
00:06:07,028 --> 00:06:08,949
Right speech, right action, right livelihood.

80
00:06:09,250 --> 00:06:16,976
So you have those three ways in the Eightfold Path, but you can see that each religion does put an accent on one of the ways.

81
00:06:17,596 --> 00:06:20,519
Buddhism obviously tends to be right understanding.

82
00:06:20,779 --> 00:06:24,682
A lot of its practices are about understanding things.

83
00:06:26,524 --> 00:06:35,233
I mean, there is the heart development, but if you were to categorize Buddhism, you'd put it in the path of understanding, I think, first of all.

84
00:06:35,653 --> 00:06:36,934
Because that was the Buddha's own

85
00:06:37,132 --> 00:06:37,653
path.

86
00:06:38,935 --> 00:06:43,620
You don't hear of the Buddha practicing metta before his liberation.

87
00:06:44,742 --> 00:06:50,288
I'm sure he did, but I don't know anywhere in scriptures where that's pointed to.

88
00:06:51,449 --> 00:06:58,077
It was more the Jhanic thing based on the breath and these mortification things, but you don't get

89
00:06:59,341 --> 00:07:03,226
Yet in his writings, he obviously pushes metta, he sees the importance of it.

90
00:07:04,007 --> 00:07:15,004
And there seems to be some hint somewhere, I'm working on it, where the Buddha says that metta alone is a path of liberation.

91
00:07:15,024 --> 00:07:24,598
But I haven't got proper proof, scriptural proof of that yet.

92
00:07:24,620 --> 00:07:24,959
Um...

93
00:07:26,644 --> 00:07:32,233
And the path of love, I think most of us would agree, you know, Christianity is very much about love.

94
00:07:32,254 --> 00:07:38,083
It's a guru, it's a relationship with Jesus, Jesus Christ, and becoming like Jesus.

95
00:07:38,483 --> 00:07:43,110
So, you know, as you know, I've been doing this walk with St. Francis, Camino St. Francis.

96
00:07:43,129 --> 00:07:47,257
So he's a very great example of that.

97
00:07:47,276 --> 00:07:49,420
And the fact that he got the stigmata.

98
00:07:49,721 --> 00:07:53,867
So now, of course, in Christian terms, he was given that by Jesus.

99
00:07:54,353 --> 00:08:00,982
by Jesus or by God or whatever as a little gift, even though it hurts and bleeds.

100
00:08:02,363 --> 00:08:22,891
But I think we would probably think of it more as such a deep identification that the body, such a deep identification through concentration exercise that the actual manifestation of Christ's body begins to manifest in his own.

101
00:08:23,783 --> 00:08:25,103
So we know the power of mind.

102
00:08:26,545 --> 00:08:29,649
That would make more sense to me anyway.

103
00:08:29,668 --> 00:08:31,190
So definitely the path of love.

104
00:08:31,651 --> 00:08:34,053
But it's also got the path of good works.

105
00:08:34,293 --> 00:08:42,143
And then if you were thinking about good works, in a sense you'd have to see it as Islam.

106
00:08:42,202 --> 00:08:44,184
Because Islam is very much on the will of God.

107
00:08:44,706 --> 00:08:46,788
The will of God, the will of action.

108
00:08:47,087 --> 00:08:47,649
Doing things.

109
00:08:47,828 --> 00:08:50,652
And of course it exemplified mainly in their jihad.

110
00:08:51,525 --> 00:08:57,154
The jihad, Muhammad said that the inner jihad was much more important than the outer one.

111
00:08:57,375 --> 00:08:58,296
But there's still the jihad.

112
00:08:59,597 --> 00:09:01,601
You know, force, will, and all that.

113
00:09:01,881 --> 00:09:07,451
So all these three paths you find, I think, in religions, but you get an accent one way or the other.

114
00:09:08,211 --> 00:09:18,106
And probably, I mean, probably the most balanced in a way, or at least seemingly so, I'm not sure about the good works business, but Hinduism.

115
00:09:18,727 --> 00:09:24,475
as many saints on both sides, the Bhakti, the devotional, and the insight one.

116
00:09:25,876 --> 00:09:27,940
I can't remember some of the devotional ones.

117
00:09:27,960 --> 00:09:32,004
I can't remember.

118
00:09:32,024 --> 00:09:32,666
Ramakrishna.

119
00:09:33,567 --> 00:09:38,592
But the insight ones, like Ramana Maharshi,

120
00:09:39,197 --> 00:09:47,210
who's very modern, and also somebody I really like, Nisigartha Maharaj, Sri Nisigartha Maharaj.

121
00:09:47,230 --> 00:09:49,153
His book, I Am That, I think is quite remarkable.

122
00:09:52,378 --> 00:10:01,893
So, that's a sort of, shall we say, a run through of the types that I see anyway.

123
00:10:01,913 --> 00:10:04,176
I can comment on that over the weekend.

124
00:10:06,602 --> 00:10:16,177
But what we're interested in now, of course, is how the Buddha explains this whole business about belief and no dogmas.

125
00:10:16,197 --> 00:10:23,207
And the main one that I'm sure you've all heard of is the Kalama Sutta.

126
00:10:24,730 --> 00:10:33,623
And we'll just read it through, mainly just to get the flavour of the discourse and the way that what comes across on the discourses are

127
00:10:35,610 --> 00:10:40,456
I mean, it's formalized because it has to be formalized for the oral tradition.

128
00:10:40,635 --> 00:10:45,640
But you do get a feel for the sorts of conversations that would have carried on.

129
00:10:45,660 --> 00:10:52,006
And the sort of Socratic thing where you're asking the person a question and they have to give you an answer.

130
00:10:52,927 --> 00:10:55,029
That's very much all the way through the scriptures.

131
00:10:56,091 --> 00:11:04,099
Although the Buddha gives talks, he's very much in conversation, starting off with some sort of problem that's been brought in.

132
00:11:05,732 --> 00:11:14,481
And he always sort of leans the conversation to a point, to really, to find out what the person's opinion is, where they are.

133
00:11:15,283 --> 00:11:17,905
And then he tends to show the error of that.

134
00:11:19,106 --> 00:11:24,292
And then when they see the error of it, they're open to his own understanding.

135
00:11:24,493 --> 00:11:29,697
And then he darts in with his own understanding, and lonely time, for the most part, they all...

136
00:11:30,606 --> 00:11:31,888
They all take him as their teacher.

137
00:11:31,927 --> 00:11:32,509
Not always.

138
00:11:32,729 --> 00:11:39,155
Some go away clicking their tongs.

139
00:11:39,176 --> 00:11:47,446
So here's the Blessed One and he's arrived at Kesaputta amongst the people called the Kalamas.

140
00:11:47,466 --> 00:11:49,408
Now the Kalamas of Kesaputta heard.

141
00:11:49,467 --> 00:11:55,914
It is said that the ascetic Gautama, the Sakya son who went forth from the Sakya family, has arrived in Kesaputta.

142
00:11:55,934 --> 00:11:59,719
Now a good report about the Master Gautama has been circulating.

143
00:12:00,322 --> 00:12:14,559
Now the Blessed One is an Arhat, perfectly enlightened, accomplished in true knowledge and conduct, fortunate, knower of the world, unsurpassed leader of persons to be tamed, and teacher of Devas and humans, the Enlightened One, the Blessed One.

144
00:12:14,580 --> 00:12:15,861
So that's what we chant every morning.

145
00:12:15,881 --> 00:12:18,544
That's a basic formula.

146
00:12:18,565 --> 00:12:28,437
And having realised with his own direct knowledge this world, with its Devas, Mara and Brahma, this population with its ascetics and Brahmans, with its Devas and humans, he makes it known to others.

147
00:12:28,517 --> 00:12:29,638
He teaches a Dharma,

148
00:12:29,904 --> 00:12:32,606
that is good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end.

149
00:12:32,868 --> 00:12:38,793
With the right meaning and expression he reveals a spiritual life that is perfectly complete and purified.

150
00:12:39,212 --> 00:12:43,798
So he's obviously got a very good reputation by the time he gets to the Kalamas.

151
00:12:43,817 --> 00:12:44,798
That's quite a peon, isn't it?

152
00:12:45,980 --> 00:12:50,322
So then the Kalamas approach him, you see, and they pay homage.

153
00:12:50,504 --> 00:12:55,268
It's interesting how various people paid homage depending on their relationship to the teacher.

154
00:12:56,168 --> 00:12:57,549
It seems though the highest

155
00:12:57,934 --> 00:13:00,259
the highest zombies was to walk around the seat three times.

156
00:13:01,561 --> 00:13:05,326
Others would just Anjali, you know, bring their hands together.

157
00:13:05,868 --> 00:13:10,215
And others would just call out their name and their clan and then take a seat.

158
00:13:10,855 --> 00:13:15,082
So there's all sort of varied ways in which you would approach somebody.

159
00:13:17,019 --> 00:13:22,748
Well, it says, some exchanged greetings with him, and after greetings and cordial talk, they sat down to one side.

160
00:13:22,927 --> 00:13:26,273
Some resoluted him revelentially and sat down to one side.

161
00:13:26,352 --> 00:13:28,897
Some remained silent and sat down to one side.

162
00:13:28,937 --> 00:13:40,192
Then they said to him, Venerable sir, some ascetics and Brahmins who come to Kesaputta explain and elucidate their own doctrines, but disparage, debunk, revile, and vilify the doctrines of others.

163
00:13:41,590 --> 00:13:50,883
But then some other ascetics and Brahmins come to Kesaputta and they too explain and elucidate their doctrines but disparage, debunk, revile and vilify the doctrines of others.

164
00:13:50,903 --> 00:13:57,152
For us, Venerable Sir, there is perplexity and doubt as to which of these good ascetics speaks the truth and which speaks false.

165
00:13:58,653 --> 00:14:01,818
So now here's the famous passage, you see.

166
00:14:01,839 --> 00:14:05,683
So it is fitting for you to be perplexed, O Kalamas.

167
00:14:05,703 --> 00:14:07,005
It is fitting for you to be in doubt.

168
00:14:07,426 --> 00:14:11,412
Doubt has arisen in you about the perplexing matter, you see.

169
00:14:11,695 --> 00:14:15,379
So he agrees with them that they are in fact confused.

170
00:14:15,399 --> 00:14:17,741
And then come calamus.

171
00:14:17,761 --> 00:14:19,804
So now this very famous statement.

172
00:14:19,865 --> 00:14:39,187
Do not go by oral tradition, by lineage of teaching, by hearsay, by a collection of texts, by logic, by inferential reasoning, by reasoned cogitation, by the acceptance of a view after pondering it, by seeming competence of the speaker, or because you think the ascetic is our teacher.

173
00:14:40,163 --> 00:14:52,195
But when you know for yourselves, these things are unwholesome, these things are blameable, these things are censured by the wise, these things, if undertaken in practice, lead to harm and suffering, then you should abandon them.

174
00:14:53,576 --> 00:14:59,201
So these four categories really cover everything.

175
00:14:59,342 --> 00:15:09,613
So we're talking about spiritual authority, scriptural authority, oral tradition, lineage of teaching, hearsay, collection of texts,

176
00:15:10,268 --> 00:15:13,111
That's where the fundamentalists place themselves, isn't it?

177
00:15:13,131 --> 00:15:18,938
They place themselves directly into their texts, what the text says.

178
00:15:20,041 --> 00:15:22,364
And then you get the four rational grounds.

179
00:15:22,864 --> 00:15:28,432
So logic, inferential reasoning, reasoned cogitation, and accepting of you after pondering it.

180
00:15:28,892 --> 00:15:30,433
So this is more the modern thing, isn't it?

181
00:15:31,034 --> 00:15:37,102
So you've got fundamentalists, you've got people who will only look at the texts, and that's it.

182
00:15:37,724 --> 00:15:43,991
And even though they have a reason to it, they'll only accept what has been reasoned in the past.

183
00:15:44,272 --> 00:15:47,696
Fundamentalists are very much based in the past.

184
00:15:48,437 --> 00:16:01,753
Whereas the modernists, I mean, by that people brought up in the Enlightenment, the European Enlightenment, really relying also on their own rationality, on their own logic.

185
00:16:02,394 --> 00:16:04,316
Even that you can't depend upon.

186
00:16:04,336 --> 00:16:07,360
You can't depend upon your own logical thinking.

187
00:16:07,794 --> 00:16:11,681
Because remember, all logical thinking has to be based on a premise.

188
00:16:12,221 --> 00:16:13,823
If the premise is wrong, that's the end of it.

189
00:16:13,844 --> 00:16:28,485
So, I mean, I think that's one of the, how can we say, one of the doubts of present day people, that you can't believe anything because beliefs in the past have caused such a huge problem.

190
00:16:28,566 --> 00:16:36,317
So, for instance, once you believe you're in a racist understanding, then you end up with some form of narcissism.

191
00:16:36,652 --> 00:17:05,510
if you believe in the proletariat and all that sort of stuff you end up with a form of communism so but that if the premise is wrong then the whole thing becomes quite nasty and evil and these days of course we're stuck with this capitalist consumerism materialistic capitalism which is a world religion and and that's it and and the basis we know the base i mean most thinking people know that the basis is is greed and and all that it shouldn't be there but um

192
00:17:06,384 --> 00:17:13,054
It's that understanding that you cannot trust your logical thing.

193
00:17:13,074 --> 00:17:20,623
You always have to go back to the premise to see whether what you're basing all this fantastic architecture of philosophy on.

194
00:17:21,104 --> 00:17:23,847
And if that's wrong, then the whole thing's a complete waste of time.

195
00:17:24,307 --> 00:17:24,969
Worse.

196
00:17:24,989 --> 00:17:25,930
It creates a lot of problems.

197
00:17:27,972 --> 00:17:30,355
And then, of course, there are authoritative persons.

198
00:17:31,076 --> 00:17:33,539
So impressive speakers and respected teachers.

199
00:17:35,832 --> 00:17:44,242
And that gives us our breakdown really.

200
00:17:45,523 --> 00:17:48,448
So that depends on your relationship to somebody.

201
00:17:50,269 --> 00:18:01,545
And there's a later one which I'll quote a bit later concerning how the Buddha says that people should actually find a critique about him.

202
00:18:01,744 --> 00:18:03,928
How do they know that he's fully liberated?

203
00:18:04,929 --> 00:18:05,028
Okay.

204
00:18:05,346 --> 00:18:07,328
So he doesn't even let himself off the hook.

205
00:18:09,051 --> 00:18:27,734
So then, of course, the conversation, now, once he's cleared the boards and said, look, don't believe anything, but then he puts to them really a manner of Socratic conversation where he asks a question and they answer him.

206
00:18:27,755 --> 00:18:28,935
So he's very basic, you see.

207
00:18:28,976 --> 00:18:34,542
What do you think, Kalama, is when greed, hatred, delusion arise in a person, is it for their welfare or harm?

208
00:18:35,079 --> 00:18:36,301
For their harm, sir.

209
00:18:38,766 --> 00:18:43,932
Calama is a person who is greedy, hating and deluded, overpowered by greed, hatred and delusion.

